        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Though no man of science but a simple bookkeeper, I have read and admired in the highest degree all your immortal works. My dear little wife, <hi rend="underline">who understands and loves you</hi>, having presented me yesterday with a pretty boy, I have taken the liberty to give him your illustrious name.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I most humbly beg to ask your kind permission, and promise to make him <hi rend="underline">an honorable man</hi>.</p>
<p>Believe me, | Dear Sir, | Your humble servant | Carl Beger. <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">Hamburg, on Charles Darwins | 70<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. Birthday. <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/><ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Charles Darwin Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi>. | FRS | England</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Beger’s wife was Emma Friedrike Caroline Dalchow; their son, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_8124.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Darwin Richard Beger</ref>, was born on 11 February 1877.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD was in fact 68 on 12 February 1877.</note>
        </div>        
            
